Background

I explore vegan. vegan is an R library that features in day to day working of a community ecologist. It would be great to know a few cases where the package comes in handy.

Load data

We load some inbuilt data, BCI, that come with the vegan package.

data("BCI")

Seems there are a lot of data here, we can check the dimensions of the data.frame using the dim function from base R package.

dim(BCI)
## [1]  50 225

Another way of getting the number of species in the data-set is to use specnumber() function in vegan package.

specnumber(BCI)

It is possible to estimate the number of species in the pool using specpool() function in R. Actually, there are 225 species, but the estimator gives values from 236 to 247 with some standard errors around them.

specpool(BCI, smallsample = TRUE)
##     Species     chao chao.se  jack1 jack1.se    jack2     boot  boot.se  n
## All     225 236.3732 6.54361 245.58 5.650522 247.8722 235.6862 3.468888 50

Calculating selected diversity indices

Here is a data-set of 50 plots indicating number of individuals of species of trees counted i each plot. Typical ecological survey work.

We can go ahead and calculate species diversity in the 50 plots using shannon index. There are also indices like simpson or invsimpson that one can calculate from the data-set.

Some plots comparing the indices

The indices are quite related to each other as indicated in the following plots.

Relationship between shannon and simpson indices of diversity.

plot(diversity(BCI, index = 'shannon'), diversity(BCI, index = 'simpson')) # Kind of linear

Relationship between shannon and invsimpson indices of diversity.

plot(diversity(BCI, index = 'shannon'), diversity(BCI, index = 'invsimpson'))

Relationship between simpson and invsimpson indices of diversity.

plot(diversity(BCI, index = 'simpson'), diversity(BCI, index = 'invsimpson')) # curvilinear relationship

Species cummulative curve

Further, we can plot species accumulation curve for the data-set. This is showing how the number of species vary with number of plots sampled. Normally the curve flattens at some point in which case additional sampling does not yield any more new species.

plot(specaccum(comm = BCI, method = 'random', permutations = 100))

# Other methods include rarefaction, site, collector, exact, coleman

Detrended correspondence analysis

Lastly, we can check for detrended correspondence analysis by plot using decorana() function.

plot(decorana(BCI))

Working with mite data

This has two separate data-frames, one for species per plot and the other for the environmental variables recorded from the same sampling plots as the species.

fort <- fortify(nmds1)
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = subset(fort, Score == 'sites'),
             mapping = aes(x = NMDS1, y = NMDS2),
             color = 'black',
             alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_segment(data = subset(fort, Score == 'species'),
               mapping = aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = NMDS1, yend = NMDS2),
               arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.015, 'npc'),
                             type = 'closed'),
               color = 'darkgray',
               size = 0.8) +
  geom_text(data = subset(fort, Score == 'species'),
            mapping = aes(label = Label, x = NMDS1 * 1.1, y = NMDS2 * 1.1)) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 0, linetype = 'dashed', size = 0.8, color = 'gray') +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 0), linetype = 'dashed', size = 0.8, color = 'gray') +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),

p3 <- ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = subset(fort, Score == 'sites'),
             mapping = aes(x = NMDS1, y = NMDS2, color = mite.env$Shrub),
             alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_segment(data = subset(fort, Score == 'species'),
               mapping = aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = NMDS1, yend = NMDS2),
               arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.015, 'npc'),
                             type = 'closed'),
               color = 'darkgray',
               size = 0,
               alpha = 0) +
  geom_text(data = subset(fort, Score == 'species'),
            mapping = aes(label = Label, x = NMDS1 * 1.1, y = NMDS2 * 1.1),
            alpha = 0) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 0, linetype = 'dashed', size = 0.8, color = 'gray') +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 0), linetype = 'dashed', size = 0.8, color = 'gray') +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        axis.line = element_line(color = 'black'),
        legend.position = c(0.8, 0.2)) +
  scale_color_discrete("Shrubs")
p3

ggarrange(p3, p2, ncol = 1)
